public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) return false;
        double val = Math.pow(3, Math.floor(Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)));
        return val == n;
    }
}
```
Here's a breakdown of how the solution works:

1. We first check if `n` is less than 1, in which case it's not a power of 3. If it is, we proceed.
2. We calculate the log of `n` to the base 3 using `Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)`. This gives us the log of `n` to the base 3, which is the logarithm of the power of 3.
3. We take the floor of this value using `Math.floor()` to get the largest integer less than or equal to the log.
4. We calculate the value of 3 raised to this power using `Math.pow(3, ...)`. This gives us the closest power of 3 less than or equal to `n`.
5. We compare this value to `n` using `==`. If they are equal, then `n` is indeed a power of 3.

This solution has a time complexity of O(1) because it uses constant-time operations and no loops or recursion.

Note that this solution assumes that the input `n` is an integer, as specified in the problem statement. If `n` can be a non-integer value, this solution would need to be modified accordingly.

